Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his platoon. Quietly, he got up from his cot, put on his combat suit, threw his body armor over it, and took his things out of the locker, being careful with a certain small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed hung from there, like his breathing apparatus or his special glasses. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled a lighter out of one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short drag before opening the door slightly. In the last week, he had to come up with quite a few things to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, because it usually didn't work and only a faint noise came from the speakers.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Platoon Leader Nemic approaching him.
"Yes," answered Cohren.
"With what do you want to try it this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith and a few others already came towards him in full gear.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What did you wake up to?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting for whatever you've come up with today. And secondly, the assault troops, who are the first to rise, are allowed to choose their morning ration," answered one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Sergeant," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm sounded in the barracks. Inside, he heard muffled cursing and people running around in confusion.
"Come on, Valturi," said Nemic. "One would think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my people from the training camp have learned it," replied Cohren, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and company leaders also know that they have to rise before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, others more annoyed.
"Good morning," said Cohren in a good mood.
"With all due respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up like that?" asked a sergeant of the assault troops.
"Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn't sleep through them," said Cohren.
"Pack all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a lieutenant colonel and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for supervising and supporting them together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second assault division, second army. Before they were combined, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operating base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid being spotted by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and on the ground to combat them.
"A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds," said Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward operating base outside Ianlos. We will support the ground attack," answered Cohren and pulled on his cigarette. He gave Craith partial credit for starting him smoking, but a year in the field changed a man, so he said nothing.
"Shit. It's getting worse at the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news says: 'Support the war effort. Send help to the Kurgan Front.' How about some help for the Howland Front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're going with the first armed platoon and don't have to run. Hauptmann Shaw should already be there."
“Did Shaw make it clear that we have a ride?”, asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
“Yes. He's honestly not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but you can tolerate him.”
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and put on his backpack. “All units of the Exodus Company will meet at the West Vehicle Park when they are ready. We will depart with the first armed convoy at 0500.”
He received answers from the platoon leaders in seconds. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking corporals when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren had the feeling he had known them for ages, even though it was at most two years. They were platoon leaders, although Craith had been leading the second convoy for a week, after the previous leader had been discharged for medical reasons following being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On their way to the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four armored infantry carriers. Their crews were walking around, ensuring their machines were ready for action. Cohren quickly spotted Major Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the commander of the armed convoy. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came towards them, as always with an expressionless face.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said, Cohren was slower, while he looked at Cohren's pistol holster and then looked up again. "The company is ready, I assume?"
